		<div class="postbody">
						<div id="post_content1480">

						<h3 ><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1480#p1480">Re: Learning Resources</a></h3>

													<ul class="post-buttons">
																																									<li>
							<a href="./posting.php?mode=quote&amp;f=4&amp;p=1480" title="Reply with quote" class="button button-icon-only">
								<i class="icon fa-quote-left fa-fw" aria-hidden="true"></i><span class="sr-only">Quote</span>
							</a>
						</li>
														</ul>
							
						<p class="author">
									<a class="unread" href="./viewtopic.php?p=1480#p1480" title="Post">
						<i class="icon fa-file fa-fw icon-lightgray icon-md" aria-hidden="true"></i><span class="sr-only">Post</span>
					</a>
								<span class="responsive-hide">by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=2" style="color: #AA0000;" class="username-coloured">justine</a></strong> &raquo; </span><time datetime="2020-03-21T15:06:02+00:00">Sat Mar 21, 2020 3:06 pm</time>
			</p>
			
			
			
			<div class="content">Hi Grailer,<br>
<br>
First, I realize I wasn't clear about my first "welcome" post... I moved your question into a new topic and gave it a title. Please feel free to edit the title if you don't like it. <br>
<br>
Anyway,<br>
<br>
I'm working on a new version of the build guide that's much clearer and more sequential. That's  here: <a href="https://skysedge.us/rotarycellphone/build/" class="postlink">https://skysedge.us/rotarycellphone/build/</a>, and I've been updating it as I go. I plan to have it entirely done today, or at least this weekend.<br>
<br>
You may find that the process appears less daunting after seeing this new version, but even so you're correct that it's not a project for beginners.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure I have a go-to resource for self learning this kind of thing. The only thing I can think of right now that doesn't involve social interaction is to point you to Youtube. I haven't thought to identify a channel specifically for learning proper soldering technique, etc, but if someone knows of a good one perhaps they can post here.<br>
<br>
In the next few weeks I'll be starting to dive more deeply into the design for the "next generation" version that will run on the 4G network and have other neat things (I'm thinking of an actual mechanical bell inside, and some other changes), and my goal for that version is that it be a complete and easy-to-assemble kit that anyone can do. If I can figure out the FCC licensing (I've been communicating with someone about this) it's even possible that it could also be released as a complete product in addition to the kit, though still open source of course.<br>
<br>
~Justine</div>

			
			
									
									
						</div>

